ce of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin; Yorkshire): habitational name from a place in northern France of which the identity is not clear, though it is probably Sainville in Eure-et-Loire, so called from Old French <i>saisne</i> ‘Saxon’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. Compare   Savel  ,   Savell  , and   Savelle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Savel","meanings":["Slovak and Czech (<b>Šavel</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Šavel</i>, Hebrew <i>Shaul</i> (see   Saul  ). It may be a nickname for a godless person, from the archaic word <i>šavel</i>, which is derived from the Biblical name.","Slovenian (<b>Šavel</b>): probably from an old spelling of the Biblical personal name <i>Savel</i> (see   Saul  , compare 2 above). Alternatively, perhaps a nickname or a topographic name from an old vernacular spelling of the same plant name as in 4 below.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Šavelj</b>: probably a nickname or a topographic name from the plant name <i>š(č)avelj</i> ‘sorrel (Rumex acetosa)’."]},{"name":"Savelle","meanings":["English: variant of   Saville  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Savell","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Saville  ."]},{"name":"Seville","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Saville  ."]},{"name":"Saffell","meanings":["English (Essex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Safugel</i> (Old Norse <i>sǽfogl</i> ‘sea-bird, especially the cormorant’), not recorded as a personal name in Scandinavia, but common in England after the Norman Conquest. In some cases with voicing of intervocalic /f/ to /v/, there may have been confusion with   Saville  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Saville II was born in 1180, in Halifax, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir John Savile Lord Halifax, was 20 and his mother, Dorothea FitzWilliam, was 20. He married Agnes d'Aldwark. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1225, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1180–1225":"1180–1225","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1195–1231":"1195–1231","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1219–1280":"1219–1280","1235–1291":"1235–1291","1160–1192":"1160–1192","1160–1195":"1160–1195","1231":"1231","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1192":"1192","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","Abt 1172":"umbes 1172","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1219":"1219","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornhill, Metropolitan Borough of Kirklees, West Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United K